---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ToolSchema from '../../components/ToolSchema.astro';
import RelatedTools from '../../components/RelatedTools.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import ContentFooter from '../../components/ContentFooter.astro';
import Sources from '../../components/Sources.astro';
import DisclaimerBanner from '../../components/DisclaimerBanner.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Ideal Weight Calculator - Free Clinical Weight Formula Estimator | ToolzTotal"
  description="Calculate your ideal body weight range using Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi clinical formulas side-by-side. Free client-side tool with frame size."
  canonicalUrl="https://toolztotal.com/health/ideal-weight-calculator"
>
  <ToolSchema
    toolName="Ideal Weight Calculator"
    toolSlug="ideal-weight-calculator"
    categoryName="Health & Fitness"
    categorySlug="health"
    description="Calculate your ideal body weight range using Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi clinical formulas side-by-side. Free client-side tool with frame size."
  faqs={[
    { question: "How is ideal body weight calculated?", answer: "Ideal body weight is estimated using several historical clinical formulas, including the Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi equations. These formulas use your height (specifically inches over 5 feet) and biological sex as primary inputs. They were originally designed for adjusting drug dosages in pharmacology but have become standard reference estimates for general fitness." },
    { question: "What is the difference between the Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi formulas?", answer: "The Hamwi formula (1964) is the oldest and generally yields the highest weight targets. The Devine formula (1974) is the most widely used in medical settings. The Robinson (1983) and Miller (1983) formulas were developed later to resolve statistical offsets in the older equations, with Miller yielding slightly higher weights for shorter individuals and Robinson yielding slightly lower weights overall." },
    { question: "How does frame size affect ideal weight calculations?", answer: "Bone structure and frame size significantly impact weight distribution. Standard formulas assume a medium frame size. A small frame adjustment subtracts 10% from the formula baseline, while a large frame adjustment adds 10% to account for denser skeletal structure and muscle potential." },
    { question: "Why is the BMI healthy weight range different from clinical formulas?", answer: "Clinical formulas estimate a single point value representing average ideal weight. The BMI healthy weight range provides a broad span (representing BMIs from 18.5 to 24.9) that accommodates natural variations in muscle mass, bone density, and individual body structure." },
    { question: "Is my physical data kept private?", answer: "Yes, absolutely. ToolzTotal operates 100% client-side. Your gender, height, and calculations remain fully local inside your browser. No data is ever transmitted, tracked, or saved on any server." },
    { question: "Why do different ideal weight formulas give different results?", answer: "Different formulas (Devine, Robinson, Miller, Hamwi) were developed at different times using slightly different base weights and scaling factors. For example, the Devine formula is the medical standard for drug dosing, while the Miller formula scales down values slightly to account for smaller average frame sizes." },
    { question: "How do I determine my body frame size?", answer: "You can determine your frame size by wrapping your thumb and index finger around your wrist at the bony point. If they overlap, you have a small frame; if they touch tip-to-tip, you have a medium frame; if there is a gap, you have a large frame. You can also measure wrist circumference with a tape measure." },
    { question: "Is ideal body weight the same as healthy body weight?", answer: "No, ideal body weight is a mathematical estimate based on statistical averages. A healthy body weight depends on your body composition (muscle-to-fat ratio), physical fitness, blood pressure, and cardiovascular health, meaning a person can be highly healthy while weighing more than their calculated ideal weight." },
    { question: "Why is ideal body weight used for medical prescriptions?", answer: "Many medications distribute primarily into lean muscle and body water rather than adipose fat tissue. Dosing these medications based on total body weight in obese patients can lead to dangerous overdoses, making ideal body weight the standard clinical safety index." },
    { question: "Can muscular people rely on ideal body weight formulas?", answer: "No, ideal body weight formulas do not account for muscle mass. Because muscle is dense and heavy, active individuals and weightlifters will naturally weigh more than their calculated mathematical ideal, even while maintaining excellent physical fitness and low body fat." }
  ]}
  />

  <div class="max-w-[1400px] mx-auto px-4 md:px-6 py-12 md:py-20">
    <Breadcrumbs
      categoryName="Health & Fitness"
      categorySlug="health"
      toolName="Ideal Weight Calculator"
      toolSlug="ideal-weight-calculator"
    />
  <DisclaimerBanner category="health" />


    <!-- Header Section -->
    <div class="max-w-4xl mb-12">
      <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 border border-hairline bg-canvas px-3 py-1 rounded-full mb-6 shadow-lvl1">
        <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-emerald-500"></span>
        <span class="text-xs font-mono text-body uppercase tracking-wider">Free Tool</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-4 text-pretty">
        Free Ideal Body Weight Calculator
      </h1>
      <p class="text-body text-base md:text-lg font-sans leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        Estimate your ideal weight range using major clinical formulas (Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi) side-by-side, with frame size adjustments and BMI comparison ranges.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Main Grid -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-10 items-start">
      
      <!-- Left Column: Inputs (5 cols) -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-5 bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-lvl2 space-y-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans border-b border-hairline pb-3">Your Profile</h2>
        
        <!-- Unit Toggle -->
        <div>
          <label class="block text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-2">Unit System</label>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-2">
            <button id="btn-metric" class="h-10 border border-hairline bg-canvas-soft-2 text-ink rounded-lg font-sans text-sm font-semibold transition-colors cursor-pointer border-hairline-strong shadow-lvl1">Metric (cm/kg)</button>
            <button id="btn-imperial" class="h-10 border border-hairline bg-canvas text-body rounded-lg font-sans text-sm transition-colors cursor-pointer hover:border-hairline-strong shadow-lvl1">Imperial (in/lbs)</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Gender -->
        <div>
          <label class="block text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-2">Biological Sex</label>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-2">
            <button id="btn-male" class="h-10 border border-hairline bg-canvas-soft-2 text-ink rounded-lg font-sans text-sm font-semibold transition-colors cursor-pointer border-hairline-strong shadow-lvl1">Male</button>
            <button id="btn-female" class="h-10 border border-hairline bg-canvas text-body rounded-lg font-sans text-sm transition-colors cursor-pointer hover:border-hairline-strong shadow-lvl1">Female</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Height Input -->
        <div>
          <label for="height" id="lbl-height" class="block text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-2">Height (cm)</label>
          <input 
            type="number" 
            id="height" 
            value="175" 
            min="1" 
            class="w-full h-10 px-3 bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-lg text-sm font-sans focus:outline-none focus:border-hairline-strong text-ink transition-colors shadow-lvl1"
          />
        </div>

        <!-- Frame Size Input -->
        <div>
          <label for="frame-size" class="block text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-2">Body Frame Size</label>
          <select 
            id="frame-size" 
            class="w-full h-10 px-3 bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-lg text-sm font-sans focus:outline-none focus:border-hairline-strong text-ink transition-colors shadow-lvl1 cursor-pointer"
          >
            <option value="small">Small Frame (-10%)</option>
            <option value="medium" selected>Medium Frame (Standard)</option>
            <option value="large">Large Frame (+10%)</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Right Column: Results (7 cols) -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-7 space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-canvas border border-hairline rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-lvl2 space-y-6">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans border-b border-hairline pb-3">Ideal Weight Ratios</h2>
          
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <!-- Robinson (often considered modern standard) -->
            <div class="bg-canvas-soft border border-hairline rounded-lg p-5 flex flex-col justify-center">
              <span class="text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-1">Robinson Formula (1983)</span>
              <div class="flex items-baseline gap-1">
                <span id="res-robinson" class="text-3xl font-black text-ink font-sans tracking-tight">—</span>
                <span id="unit-robinson" class="text-xs font-mono text-mute">kg</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Devine (most widely used in medicine) -->
            <div class="bg-canvas-soft border border-hairline rounded-lg p-5 flex flex-col justify-center">
              <span class="text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-1">Devine Formula (1974)</span>
              <div class="flex items-baseline gap-1">
                <span id="res-devine" class="text-3xl font-black text-ink font-sans tracking-tight">—</span>
                <span id="unit-devine" class="text-xs font-mono text-mute">kg</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Miller Formula -->
            <div class="bg-canvas-soft border border-hairline rounded-lg p-5 flex flex-col justify-center">
              <span class="text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-1">Miller Formula (1983)</span>
              <div class="flex items-baseline gap-1">
                <span id="res-miller" class="text-3xl font-black text-ink font-sans tracking-tight">—</span>
                <span id="unit-miller" class="text-xs font-mono text-mute">kg</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Hamwi Formula -->
            <div class="bg-canvas-soft border border-hairline rounded-lg p-5 flex flex-col justify-center">
              <span class="text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute mb-1">Hamwi Formula (1964)</span>
              <div class="flex items-baseline gap-1">
                <span id="res-hamwi" class="text-3xl font-black text-ink font-sans tracking-tight">—</span>
                <span id="unit-hamwi" class="text-xs font-mono text-mute">kg</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- BMI Healthy range comparison -->
          <div class="space-y-3 pt-4 border-t border-hairline">
            <h3 class="text-xs font-mono uppercase text-mute">Healthy Weight Span (WHO BMI 18.5 - 24.9)</h3>
            <div class="bg-emerald-500/5 border border-emerald-500/10 rounded-xl p-4 flex items-center justify-between">
              <span class="text-sm font-sans text-body">Standard range for your height</span>
              <span id="res-bmi-range" class="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-500 font-sans">—</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Medical Disclaimer Box -->
          <div class="p-4 rounded-lg bg-warning-soft border border-warning-deep/20 text-warning-deep flex gap-3 text-xs md:text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 shrink-0 text-warning-deep" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01m-6.938 4h13.856c1.54 0 2.502-1.667 1.732-3L13.732 4c-.77-1.333-2.694-1.333-3.464 0L3.34 16c-.77 1.333.192 3 1.732 3z" />
            </svg>
            <p>
              <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This tool provides general estimates for informational purposes only and is not medical advice. Individual results vary based on factors this calculator does not account for. Consult a healthcare provider for personalized guidance.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Article Content -->
    <article class="mt-20 prose dark:prose-invert max-w-4xl border-t border-hairline pt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-6">The Clinical Science of Ideal Body Weight: Comparative Formulas</h2>
      <div class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>
          Determining an ideal body weight is historically rooted in pharmacology, where physicians needed calculations to determine safe and effective medication dosages. Over time, these clinical guidelines have transitioned into indicators for weight management, athletic training, and general health planning.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Comparing Clinical Ideal Weight Formulas</h3>
        <p>
          Our calculator compiles the four major historical clinical equations side-by-side to show you how different models prioritize body proportions. Each formula uses height in inches over 5 feet (60 inches) as its primary scaling factor:
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="min-w-full text-xs font-sans text-left border-collapse border border-hairline mt-4">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-canvas-soft-2 border-b border-hairline">
                <th class="p-3 font-semibold border-r border-hairline">Formula</th>
                <th class="p-3 font-semibold border-r border-hairline">Men (height H in inches over 60)</th>
                <th class="p-3 font-semibold">Women (height H in inches over 60)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold border-r border-hairline">Hamwi (1964)</td>
                <td class="p-3 border-r border-hairline">48.0 kg + 2.7 kg per inch</td>
                <td class="p-3">45.5 kg + 2.2 kg per inch</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold border-r border-hairline">Devine (1974)</td>
                <td class="p-3 border-r border-hairline">50.0 kg + 2.3 kg per inch</td>
                <td class="p-3">45.5 kg + 2.3 kg per inch</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline">
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold border-r border-hairline">Robinson (1983)</td>
                <td class="p-3 border-r border-hairline">52.0 kg + 1.9 kg per inch</td>
                <td class="p-3">49.0 kg + 1.7 kg per inch</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="bg-canvas border-b border-hairline">
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold border-r border-hairline">Miller (1983)</td>
                <td class="p-3 border-r border-hairline">56.2 kg + 1.41 kg per inch</td>
                <td class="p-3">53.1 kg + 1.36 kg per inch</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Adjusting for Frame Size and Bone Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Standard clinical formulas assume a medium skeletal frame size. However, individuals with smaller bone structures require less mass to support their stature, whereas individuals with larger skeletal structures can carry more mass healthily.
        </p>
        <p>
          To adjust for these variations, our calculator incorporates body frame size offsets. A small frame selection subtracts 10% from the formula values, while a large frame selection adds 10% to the estimates.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">BMI Healthy Weight Ranges</h3>
        <p>
          Because clinical formulas yield a single point value, they do not capture the normal range of healthy weights. To provide a more complete picture, we compare these estimates side-by-side with the WHO healthy weight range. Calculated using BMIs from 18.5 to 24.9, this range accommodates natural differences in muscle mass, hydration, and body composition.
        </p>
      
<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Historical Context of Ideal Weight Formulas</h3>
        <p>
          When interpreting the results of an ideal weight calculation, it is helpful to understand the history of the formulas. The standard formulas (such as the Devine, Robinson, and Miller equations) were not originally designed to determine aesthetic body weights or fitness targets. In 1974, Dr. Ben Devine developed his formula specifically to calculate the clearance rates of medications (such as digoxin and theophylline) in clinical hospital settings. Because drug dosing relies on the size of a patient's organs rather than their fat mass, clinicians required a standardized height-to-weight index. Over time, these equations were adopted as general health guidelines, though they have limitations for individuals with high muscle mass or non-standard frame sizes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Because these formulas only account for height and biological sex, they tend to underestimate ideal weights for very tall individuals and overestimate them for shorter people. Additionally, they do not take age-related bone density changes or muscle development into consideration.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Adjusting for Body Frame Size and Structure</h3>
        <p>
          To make ideal weight estimates more practical, clinicians often adjust the baseline values by 10% based on your body frame size (small, medium, or large). A person with a large frame has thicker bones and wider shoulders, meaning their ideal healthy weight will fall near the upper limit of the calculated range. Conversely, an individual with a delicate skeletal structure or small frame will carry less bone mass and should target the lower end of the range. You can determine your frame size by measuring the circumference of your wrist relative to your height.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">The Clinical Transition to Body Composition Metrics</h3>
        <p>
          In modern medical practices, weight targets are shifting away from static formulas toward personalized metrics. Measuring body fat percentage, waist circumference, and blood biomarker levels provides a far more accurate assessment of cardiorespiratory and metabolic fitness. Using this tool as a helpful starting range is recommended, but you should discuss the numbers with a qualified health professional to evaluate your overall health profile.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

  <Sources sources={[
    { label: 'National Institutes of Health (NIH)', url: 'https://www.nih.gov/' },
    { label: 'World Health Organization (WHO)', url: 'https://www.who.int/' }
  ]} />

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    
    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="max-w-4xl pt-16 mt-20 border-t border-hairline" aria-label="Frequently Asked Questions">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-8 text-pretty">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            How is ideal body weight calculated?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            Ideal body weight is estimated using several historical clinical formulas, including the Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi equations. These formulas use your height (specifically inches over 5 feet) and biological sex as primary inputs. They were originally designed for adjusting drug dosages in pharmacology but have become standard reference estimates for general fitness.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            What is the difference between the Devine, Robinson, Miller, and Hamwi formulas?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            The Hamwi formula (1964) is the oldest and generally yields the highest weight targets. The Devine formula (1974) is the most widely used in medical settings. The Robinson (1983) and Miller (1983) formulas were developed later to resolve statistical offsets in the older equations, with Miller yielding slightly higher weights for shorter individuals and Robinson yielding slightly lower weights overall.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            How does frame size affect ideal weight calculations?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            Bone structure and frame size significantly impact weight distribution. Standard formulas assume a medium frame size. A small frame adjustment subtracts 10% from the formula baseline, while a large frame adjustment adds 10% to account for denser skeletal structure and muscle potential.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            Why is the BMI healthy weight range different from clinical formulas?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            Clinical formulas estimate a single point value representing average ideal weight. The BMI healthy weight range provides a broad span (representing BMIs from 18.5 to 24.9) that accommodates natural variations in muscle mass, bone density, and individual body structure.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            Is my physical data kept private?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            Yes, absolutely. ToolzTotal operates 100% client-side. Your gender, height, and calculations remain fully local inside your browser. No data is ever transmitted, tracked, or saved on any server.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            Why do different ideal weight formulas give different results?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            Different formulas (Devine, Robinson, Miller, Hamwi) were developed at different times using slightly different base weights and scaling factors. For example, the Devine formula is the medical standard for drug dosing, while the Miller formula scales down values slightly to account for smaller average frame sizes.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            How do I determine my body frame size?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            You can determine your frame size by wrapping your thumb and index finger around your wrist at the bony point. If they overlap, you have a small frame; if they touch tip-to-tip, you have a medium frame; if there is a gap, you have a large frame. You can also measure wrist circumference with a tape measure.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            Is ideal body weight the same as healthy body weight?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            No, ideal body weight is a mathematical estimate based on statistical averages. A healthy body weight depends on your body composition (muscle-to-fat ratio), physical fitness, blood pressure, and cardiovascular health, meaning a person can be highly healthy while weighing more than their calculated ideal weight.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            Why is ideal body weight used for medical prescriptions?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            Many medications distribute primarily into lean muscle and body water rather than adipose fat tissue. Dosing these medications based on total body weight in obese patients can lead to dangerous overdoses, making ideal body weight the standard clinical safety index.
          </div>
        </details>
      
        <details class="bg-canvas ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 group">
          <summary class="px-6 py-4 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between font-sans font-semibold text-sm text-ink list-none hover:bg-canvas-soft transition-colors select-none">
            Can muscular people rely on ideal body weight formulas?
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute shrink-0 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm text-body font-sans leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline pt-4">
            No, ideal body weight formulas do not account for muscle mass. Because muscle is dense and heavy, active individuals and weightlifters will naturally weigh more than their calculated mathematical ideal, even while maintaining excellent physical fitness and low body fat.
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Related Tools Section -->
    <section class="max-w-4xl pt-16 mt-20 border-t border-hairline" aria-label="Related Tools">
      <h3 class="text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-wider text-mute mb-8">Related Health Calculators</h3>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
